{"id":"0806.4347","submitter":"Irena Knezevic","authors":"E. B. Ramayya, D. Vasileska, S. M. Goodnick, and I. Knezevic","title":"Electron mobility in silicon nanowires","comments":null,"journal-ref":"IEEE Trans. Nanotech. 6, 113 (2007)","doi":"10.1109/TNANO.2006.888521","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The low-field electron mobility in rectangular silicon nanowire (SiNW)\ntransistors was computed using a self-consistent Poisson-Schr\\\"{o}dinger-Monte\nCarlo solver. The behavior of the phonon-limited and surface-roughness-limited\ncomponents of the mobility was investigated by decreasing the wire width from\n30 nm to 8 nm, the width range capturing a crossover between two-dimensional\n(2D) and one-dimensional (1D) electron transport. The phonon-limited mobility,\nwhich characterizes transport at low and moderate transverse fields, is found\nto decrease with decreasing wire width due to an increase in the\nelectron-phonon wavefunction overlap. In contrast, the mobility at very high\ntransverse fields, which is limited by surface roughness scattering, increases\nwith decreasing wire width due to volume inversion. The importance of acoustic\nphonon confinement is also discussed briefly.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 26 Jun 2008 15:35:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-11-17"}
{"id":"0806.4348","submitter":"Nele Vandersickel","authors":"David Dudal, John Gracey, Silvio Paolo Sorella, Nele Vandersickel,\n  Henri Verschelde","title":"A refinement of the Gribov-Zwanziger approach in the Landau gauge:\n  infrared propagators in harmony with the lattice results","comments":"38 pages, 9 figures, the content of section V has been extended and\n  adapted","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev.D78:065047,2008","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.78.065047","report-no":"LTH-789","categories":"hep-th hep-lat hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Recent lattice data have reported an infrared suppressed, positivity\nviolating gluon propagator which is nonvanishing at zero momentum and a ghost\npropagator which is no longer enhanced. This paper discusses how to obtain\nanalytical results which are in qualitative agreement with these lattice data\nwithin the Gribov-Zwanziger framework. This framework allows one to take into\naccount effects related to the existence of gauge copies, by restricting the\ndomain of integration in the path integral to the Gribov region. We elaborate\nto great extent on a previous short paper by presenting additional results,\nalso confirmed by the numerical simulations. A detailed discussion on the soft\nbreaking of the BRST symmetry arising in the Gribov-Zwanziger approach is\nprovided.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 26 Jun 2008 15:43:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 4 Aug 2008 14:13:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
{"id":"0806.4349","submitter":"Jurgen Baacke","authors":"Jurgen Baacke, Nina Kevlishvili","title":"One-loop corrections to the string tension of the vortex in the Abelian\n  Higgs model","comments":"48 pages, 48 figures","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev.D78:085008,2008; Erratum-ibid.D82:129905,2010","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.82.129905","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present an exact numerical computation of the one-loop correction of the\nstring tension for the Nielsen-Olesen vortex in the Abelian Higgs model. The\ncomputations proceeds via the computation of the Euclidean Green's function for\nthe gauge, Higgs and Faddeev-Popov fields using mode functions, and taking the\nappropriate trace. Renormalization is an essential part of this computation, it\nis done by removing leading order contributions from the numerical results so\nas to make these finite, and to add the divergent parts back, after suitable\nregularization and renormalization. We encounter and solve some problems which\nare specific to gauge theories and topological solutions. The corrections to\nthe energy are found to be sizeable, but still smaller than the classical\nenergy as long as g**2 is smaller than unity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 26 Jun 2008 15:46:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-01-17"}
